        <body><div type="bibliography">
                <head>Bibliography</head>
            <p>Never publisehd before this edition.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Ἁγήμων"><supplied reason="lost">Ἁγ</supplied>ήμονος</name></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name><gap reason="lost" quantity="2" unit="character"/><orig>ε</orig><gap reason="lost" quantity="1" unit="character"/><orig>σ</orig><gap reason="lost" atLeast="2" atMost="3" unit="character"/></name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Tombe de</supplied> Hagèmôn, <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">tombe d'Untel</supplied> (ou <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">fils d'Untel</supplied>).</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Tomb of</supplied> Hagemon, <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">tomb of So-and-so</supplied> (or <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">son of So-and-so</supplied>).</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Tomba di</supplied> Hagemon, <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">tomba del tale</supplied> (o <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">figlio del tale</supplied>).</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
             <p>E. Rosamilia saw the inscription in a tomb of the West Necropolis not far from tomb W128 Cassels, where he had identified <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr123400</ref>. The tomb 
                 that corresponds best to Rosamilia's photograph seems to be W133, although this should be taken cautiously.</p>
            <p>The beginning of the lines was lost because the forecourt of the tomb was reworked and the wall was cut off. However, the name at line 1 may be restored plausibly. In funerary mentions where the first name is at the genitive case, 
                the father's name is not usually mentioned. Therefore, the second line might rather mention another dead person. Anyhow, its reading was very partial, as most letters were buried.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
